Package org.efs.dispatcher

Class EfsDispatcherThread

java.lang.Object
java.lang.Thread
org.efs.dispatcher.EfsDispatcherThread
All Implemented Interfaces:
Runnable
public final class EfsDispatcherThread extends Thread
A dispatcher thread watches a given run queue for EfsAgent instances ready to run, attempting to acquire the next ready agent. When this thread successfully acquires a agent, it has the agent execute its pending events until either 1) the agent has no more events or 2) the agent exhausts its maximum allowed event limit.

Each dispatcher has a configurable run-time maximum event (defaults to DEFAULT_MAX_EVENTS). When a agent exhausts this limit and still has events to process, the agent is placed at the end of the run queue and the agent's event limit is replenished.

A agent instance is referenced by only one dispatcher thread at a time. This means a agent is effectively single-threaded even though over time it may be dispatched by multiple, different threads.

Note: this only applies to efs dispatcher threads. Non-dispatcher threads may still access a agent object at the same time.

Author:
Charles W. Rapp

  • Method Details

    • run

      public void run()
      A dispatcher thread continues processing ready efs clients until the JVM exits. On each iteration, this thread acquires the next available agent. Then iterates over the agent's event list, delivering each event in turn. This continues until the agent either has no more events or has used up its maximum event limit. The agent is put back on the run queue and this thread goes back to the loop's top, acquiring next available agent.

      Because an efs agent is posted to only one, unique run queue and each Dispatcher thread works with only one run queue, once a dispatcher thread acquires an efs agent, it is guaranteed that no other dispatcher thread has access to the agent. Therefore, from an efs perspective, efs agent access is single-threaded.

      (Non-dispatcher threads may still access an agent simultaneously as a dispatcher thread. This is an application design decision and requires proper synchronization.)
